The malady of the King continued. He had been moved to Windsor, and some means had been taken for the conduct of ordinary business by the appointment of the Duke of York to the function of presiding over the Parliameut, now most unwontedly in the second year of its sitting. But a crisis soon occurred. On March 22, Kemp, Archbishop of Canter- bury and Lord Chaucellor, died suddenly.
